Mark all optimize methods and the codegen method as safe

There is no safety contract and I don't think any of them can actually
cause UB in more ways than passing malicious source code to rustc can.
While LtoModuleCodegen::optimize says that the returned ModuleCodegen
points into the LTO module, the LTO module has already been dropped by
the time this function returns, so if the returned ModuleCodegen indeed
points into the LTO module, we would have seen crashes on every LTO
compilation, which we don't. As such the comment is outdated.

Rollup merge of #141507 - RalfJung:atomic-intrinsics, r=bjorn3

atomic_load intrinsic: use const generic parameter for ordering

We have a gazillion intrinsics for the atomics because we encode the ordering into the intrinsic name rather than making it a parameter. This is particularly bad for those operations that take two orderings. Let's fix that!

This PR only converts `load`, to see if there's any feedback that would fundamentally change the strategy we pursue for the const generic intrinsics.

The first two commits are preparation and could be a separate PR if you prefer.

`@BoxyUwU` -- I hope this is a use of const generics that is unlikely to explode? All we need is a const generic of enum type. We could funnel it through an integer if we had to but an enum is obviously nicer...

`@bjorn3` it seems like the cranelift backend entirely ignores the ordering?

Use layout field of OperandRef and PlaceRef in codegen_intrinsic_call

This avoids having to get the function signature.

Create README.md

# 🏗️ Floor Plan to GeoJSON Map Tool

## 📌 Project Overview
This project is a web-based tool that allows users to **upload a floor plan image** (e.g., PNG, JPG, or PDF), automatically converts it into **GeoJSON format**, and displays it as an interactive map.  
It can be rendered in **2D or 3D**, similar to mapping tools like MappedIn.

---

## 🚀 Features
- 📤 Upload floor plan images.  
- 🤖 AI + Computer Vision (OpenCV / AI models) to detect rooms, walls, and pathways.  
- 🌍 Automatic conversion to **GeoJSON** format.  
- 🗺️ Interactive map display using **Leaflet.js** (2D) or **Mapbox GL JS** (3D).  
- 💾 Option to export GeoJSON for use in other GIS tools.  
- 🔧 Extensible design for multi-floor navigation and AR/VR integration.  

---

## 🔄 Workflow
1. User uploads a floor plan image.  
2. Backend processes the image → extracts walls/rooms → converts to polygons.  
3. GeoJSON file is generated and served to the frontend.  
4. The frontend fetches the GeoJSON and renders it as a navigable map.  

---

- **Backend**: Python (FastAPI / Flask), OpenCV, Shapely, GeoPandas  
- **Frontend**: React, Leaflet.js (2D), Mapbox GL / Three.js (3D)  
- **Storage**: MongoDB (GeoJSON support) or local storage

issue.title: [Feat]: Filter lift option of SPARQL queries
issue.body:
`Optimizer::optimize_graph_pattern` is designed to support optimised query evaluation. In this context it makes sense to push filters down.

I am using this library to optimise a SPARQL algebra to then generate a ZKP circuit to prove query correctness. In this context; the circuit - bindings are given; and a proof is generated to show that the bindings hold for a given dataset. In this case it is desirable to "lift" rather than "push" filters to minimise the number of filter contraints that need to be generated for the circuit.

This is a feature request to have an option in `Optimizer::optimize_graph_pattern` to "optimise for verification" or to have a new function `Optimizer::optimize_graph_pattern_verification`.

I may look into implementing this myself - @Tpt could you steer on whether a PR implementing this feature would be accepted - and if so; whether you have any preferences on API design.

comment.body:
Hi! The current optimizer is very primitive. I think in the "best" future we should have something with a set of rewrite rules and a "cost model" to guide optimization. This cost model would be provided by `sparopt` user. Oxigraph would provide a cost model where "pushed" filter are better whereas your ZKP circuit builder would provide a cost model where "lifted" filters are better. But it's a lot of work even if crates like [egg](https://crates.io/crates/egg) might make it easier.

In the the meantime, happy to have an option for that in the [`Optimizer`] struct.

pull_request.title: [Issue #49] User Story 2.3: GitHub MCP Server — github_get_issue (Template-Conformant)
pull_request.body:
- Implement in-process github MCP provider
- Expose github_get_issue tool constrained to GitHub.com
- Add token authentication with proper redaction
- Classify API errors (401/403 → fatal, 429 → retryable)
- Add unit and e2e tests
- Add static error definitions for GitHub provider to fix golangci-lint err113 violations
- Move environment variable resolution to shared ResolveEnvVar function in types package
- Update GitHub provider to use wrapped static errors instead of dynamic errors
- Add environment variable resolution to MCP server configuration
- Update GitHub provider tests to match new error message format
- Improve GitHub integration test to verify actual tool execution flow

**Related Issue**: #49: GitHub Reader Step Implementation

Implements GitHub MCP provider exposing github_get_issue tool with proper error handling, linting compliance, and comprehensive testing. The provider includes token authentication, error classification, and environment variable resolution for secure configuration management.

## Acceptance Criteria

[✓] Provider registers github_get_issue tool
[✓] Only api.github.com domain accepted
[✓] Success: Returns { title, body, state, labels } in Result and ContextWrites
[✓] Errors: Classified and written to ContextWrites.last_error
[✓] Tokens redacted from logs
[✓] Unit tests pass
[✓] All linting issues resolved with static error definitions
[✓] Environment variable resolution implemented
[ ] E2E tests pass with real GitHub API (requires .env.e2e with GITHUB_TOKEN)

## Implementation Details

- Created internal/github/provider.go with GitHub REST v3 client
- Added comprehensive parameter validation and error classification
- Implemented custom token transport for authentication
- Registered provider in MCP registry
- Added static error definitions to resolve golangci-lint violations
- Moved environment variable resolution to shared types package
- Added unit tests covering all validation scenarios
- Added e2e test framework (passes tool discovery, execution requires credentials)

- [x] I searched existing issues and discussions for duplicates
- [x] I’m using the latest version of prisma-zod-generator

### Description

Hey, 

first of all I'd like to thank you for all your great work here. It's amazing at what speed you are shipping!

Now that the schemas come out as expected I started integrating them into my application and notice that optional parameters from the prisma schema (like `userId String?`) are converted into `z.string().optional()` though in my opinion it should be `z.string().nullish()` as null is also a valid value in this case.

Explained above.

```prisma
    userId         String?
    type           PurchaseType
    customerId     String
    subscriptionId String?       @unique
    productId      String
    status         String?
    createdAt      DateTime      @default(now())
    updatedAt      DateTime      @updatedAt
}
```

```prisma
model Purchase {

    organization   Organization? @relation(fields: [organizationId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

    user           User?         @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
```
